observations.recommendation:
Establish specific guidelines in the granting of financial assistance to its constituents that would include criteria to ascertain the necessity, eligibility and veracity of the requesting party and thereby ensuring that government funds have been efficiently and effectively utilized;

Put into place a well-defined control procedure in the granting and payment of financial assistance to ensure that government funds have been safeguarded against wastage and misuse;

Maintain a database of the clients that would include among others the profiles of the clients served, the number of clients served and the type of assistance availed so as to set indicators to gauge that the objectives of socio-economic development have been achieved; and 

Establish a monitoring and evaluation procedure to assess the effectiveness of the assistance or program and efficiently develop other programs or interventions that would be responsive to the need of the City’s constituents.

Refrain from granting cash advances to accountable officers who have not settled their previous cash advances in compliance with Section 89 of P.D. No. 1445;

Enforce the liquidation of outstanding cash advances granted especially for those accountable officers that are still in active service;

Refrain from granting cash advances for special purpose to officials of other government agencies;

Establish an efficient and effective control in the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances to minimize unsettled balances; and

Strictly adhere to the guidelines set forth in COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997 in the granting and liquidation of cash advances.

We also recommend the City Accounting Office to be vigilant in monitoring unliquidated cash advances and to record within the prescribed period the liquidations of cash advances made by various accountable officers to avoid inaccuracy in reporting.

That the City Accountant’s Office and the City General Services Office must establish an effective or practical system that would ensure the expeditious and regular reconciliation of records of both offices pertaining to the City’s Property, Plant and Equipment;

For the City Accountant to verify the items in the Construction in Progress account and make the necessary adjustments in the books to reclassify the completed projects to their appropriate PPE account; and

That the Local Chief Executive should augment the needed personnel and equipment in the General Services Office and Accounting Office that would facilitate in the reconciliation and efficient maintenance of records of the PPE accounts.

Recommendations:
We recommended the management to:
Refrain from granting cash advances to accountable officers who have not settled their previous cash advances in compliance with Section 89 of P.D. No. 1445;
Enforce the liquidation of outstanding cash advances granted especially for those accountable officers that are still in active service;
Refrain from granting cash advances for special purpose to officials of other government agencies;
Establish an efficient and effective control in the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances to minimize unsettled balances; and
Strictly adhere to the guidelines set forth in COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997 in the granting and liquidation of cash advances.
We also recommend the City Accounting Office to be vigilant in monitoring unliquidated cash advances and to record within the prescribed period the liquidations of cash advances made by various accountable officers to avoid inaccuracy in reporting.

Recommendations:
We recommended that management should:
Execute a Memorandum of Agreement on all fund transfers made to barangays under the City Aid program in conformity with COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012;
Adopt stringent control measures in the release or transfer of funds to barangays taking into account the status of liquidation of the funds previously transferred to them;
Conduct close monitoring on barangays that have not yet liquidated their transferred funds or incurring delay in the liquidation thereof; and
Undertake assessment on the capabilities of the barangay officials in the implementation of the projects, especially in the procurement process, to avoid delays in the liquidation of the funds transferred.

